  "explanation": "The defendant committed a serious breach of fiduciary duty by embezzling $25,000 from their employer. White-collar crimes of this nature require a penalty that serves as both a specific and general deterrent to protect businesses and the integrity of the accounting profession. However, the court must weigh several significant mitigating factors in this case. The defendant has no prior criminal record, indicating this is an isolated lapse in judgment rather than a pattern of criminal behavior. Furthermore, the defendant has already made partial restitution, demonstrating remorse and a genuine willingness to make the victim whole. The theft was motivated by personal debt rather than a desire for illicit enrichment to fund a lavish lifestyle. Balancing the need for punishment and deterrence with the defendant's high potential for rehabilitation and the necessity of allowing them to work to complete restitution, a brief period of incarceration is warranted. This will be followed by a probationary period during which full restitution must be completed.",
  "verdict": 6
}
